docs.abstract: The virtual assistants had more than a decade to become indispensable. But they were hampered by clunky design and miscalculations, leaving room for chatbots to rise.
docs.snippet: The virtual assistants had more than a decade to become indispensable. But they were hampered by clunky design and miscalculations, leaving room for chatbots to rise.
docs.lead_paragraph: On a rainy Tuesday in San Francisco, Apple executives took the stage in a crowded auditorium to unveil the fifth-generation iPhone. The phone, which looked identical to the previous version, had a new feature that the audience was soon buzzing about: Siri, a virtual assistant.

headline.main: How Siri, Alexa and Google Assistant Lost the A.I. Race
headline.print_headline: Alexa and Siri Frittered Away  Their Big Lead in the A.I. Race

byline.original: By Brian X. Chen, Nico Grant and Karen Weise

docs.abstract: The Amazon mini-series about the rise and fall of a 1970s band mixes music, nostalgia, romance and a heavy dose of soap opera.
docs.snippet: The Amazon mini-series about the rise and fall of a 1970s band mixes music, nostalgia, romance and a heavy dose of soap opera.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Amazon Prime Video mini-series “Daisy Jones & the Six” has been positioned as the first big-fun hit of the year, a glossy and nostalgic pop-music drama in the vein of “Almost Famous” based in part on the stormy history of Fleetwood Mac. It’s big, all right, but most of the fun seems to have been lost in the mix — someone dialed down the romance and escapism and slid up the knob labeled “solemn tear-jerker.” You’re expecting “Rhiannon,” but what comes out of the speakers is more like “MacArthur Park.”

headline.main: ‘Daisy Jones & the Six’ Review: Between Rock and a Soft Place
headline.print_headline: Behind the ’70s Music, a Lot of Soap Opera
